File: platform/browser-extension/src/browser-commands/helpers.ts, line 104-106.

Current code:
```typescript
if (result.error) {
  sendToServer({ jsonrpc: '2.0', error: { code: JSONRPC_INVALID_PARAMS, message: result.error }, id });
  return null;
}
```

`result.error` is a string from a MAIN-world script execution (chrome.scripting.executeScript). It could contain file paths or internal details from the page context. The fix is simple — wrap it: `message: sanitizeErrorMessage(result.error)`. The import already exists at line 3.

Note: the `sendErrorResult` function at line 112 already sanitizes via `sanitizeErrorMessage(toErrorMessage(err))`. The `extractScriptResult` function is the only unsanitized path in this file.

Also update the test in helpers.test.ts if it asserts on the exact unsanitized error string — it should still pass since test mocks sanitizeErrorMessage as identity function.
